b": 0.9991340041160583, "span": {"begin": 1150, "end": 1163}}, {"id": ["mesh:D015725"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fluconazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9889171123504639, "span": {"begin": 1168, "end": 1179}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003123"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "adenomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999997615814209, "span": {"begin": 1224, "end": 1232}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002277"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "carcinomas", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999978542327881, "span": {"begin": 1237, "end": 1247}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:653108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9916321635246277, "span": {"begin": 1348, "end": 1351}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:653108"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918590188026428, "span": {"begin": 1437, "end": 1440}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011230"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "pre-neoplastic", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9794562458992004, "span": {"begin": 1476, "end": 1490}}, {"id": ["mesh:D008113"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "liver tumors", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999980628490448, "span": {"begin": 1505, "end": 1517}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9683889150619507, "span": {"begin": 1521, "end": 1525}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10116"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "rats", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9761183857917786, "span": {"begin": 1530, "end": 1534}}], "text": "The observed increase in numbers of preneoplastic foci, usually with eosinophilic staining properties, is observed with great regularity in mode of action work of CAR activating xenobiotics where histopathology at later times has been examined. This increase in foci (mixed or eosinophilic) after 2 years was observed at tumorigenic dose levels with metofluthrin in male rats (Deguchi et al., 2009), and at tumorigenic dose levels in mice treated with phenobarbital (Jones et al., 2009). With TCPOBOP in mice, multiple eosinophilic foci were reported to co-occur along with an increased incidence of eosinophilic adenomas and carcinomas after 60 weeks of treatment (Diwan et al., 1992).  In addition, experiments where the MIE (CAR activation) is blocked have been performed with these model CAR activators. For phenobarbital and TCPOBOP in mice, the early key events and the progression to increased altered foci and hepatocellular tumors were all blocked in CAR knockout mice (Huang et al., 2005; Yamamoto et al., 2004). Foci of cellular alteration in CAR knockout mice were also prevented in an initiation-promotion model using the CAR activators cyproconazole and fluconazole (Tamura et al., 2015), and the incidence of adenomas and carcinomas was similarly decreased (Tamura et al., 2015). Thus, there is strong support for the involvement of CAR activation in these mechanisms, and that the stated sequence of key events following CAR activation leads to an increase in pre-neoplastic foci and then liver tumors in mice and rats.  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:49:13 +0000 2026"}